#. type: Plain text
#: origin/xterm-256color.txt:35
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"HINT:\n"
"\tXFree86 builds a 16 color capable xterm by default.\n"
"If you want to run vim or other color capable programs, you may\n"
"want an xterm that does more colors.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/xterm-256color.txt:39
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"1. How many colors do I have?\n"
"You can check how many colors your xterm knows with the command:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/xterm-256color.txt:41
msgid "strings /usr/X11R6/bin/xterm | grep ^color[0-9] | sort -tr +1 -n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/xterm-256color.txt:44
msgid ""
"This command has to be executed as root, since xterm is setuid and is not "
"readable by normal users.  It may print something like:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/xterm-256color.txt:50
msgid "color0 color1 ..  color14 color15"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/xterm-256color.txt:53
msgid ""
"If that is all you get, you have a 16 color xterm.  If the list keeps going "
"to color255, you already have a 256 color xterm."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/xterm-256color.txt:59
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"2. Building a 256 color xterm\n"
"If you already removed your xc tree, don't despair.  You can recompile\n"
"xterm without compiling the World.  If you don't still have the xc tree\n"
"extracted, just extract X430src-1.tgz and X430src-2.tgz.  xterm is in\n"
"the second tarball.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/xterm-256color.txt:68
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"cd xc/programs/xterm &&\n"
"rm -f *.o\n"
"xmkmf &&\n"
"sed 's/_WIDE_CHARS/_WIDE_CHARS -DOPT_256_COLORS "
"-DDFT_TERM_TYPE=xterm-color/' \\\n"
"\tMakefile > Makefile~ &&\n"
"mv Makefile~ Makefile &&\n"
"make &&\n"
"strings xterm | grep ^color[0-9] | sort -tr +1 -n\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/xterm-256color.txt:70
msgid "This time you should see a list of colors that counts to color255"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/xterm-256color.txt:76
msgid "color0 color1 ..  color254 color255"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/xterm-256color.txt:79
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"4) Install the new xterm\n"
"make install\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/xterm-256color.txt:83
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"5) Update your TERM variable\n"
"Use xterm-color as your TERM type.  You may want\n"
"something like this in your /etc/bashrc:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/xterm-256color.txt:89
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"case `tty` in\n"
"\t*/pty*|*/pts/*)\t\n"
"\texport TERM=xterm-color\n"
"\t;;\n"
"esac\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/xterm-256color.txt:94
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"6) Xdefaults\n"
"Different X apps/window managers may use either .Xresources or .Xdefaults\n"
"to change their default behavior.  Here are some things in my .Xdefaults\n"
"to make colors more enjoyable:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/xterm-256color.txt:101
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"! Pick your favorites from /usr/X11R6/lib/X11/rgb.txt\n"
"! Be sure to use the \"OneWord\" value for a color, and not\n"
"! the \"two words\" value.  \n"
"! xterm*background:       black\n"
"! xterm*foreground:       green\n"
"*loginShell:            true\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/xterm-256color.txt:105
msgid ""
"! Use color for underline attribute *VT100*colorULMode: on *VT100*underLine: "
"off"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/xterm-256color.txt:108
msgid "! Use color for the bold attribute *VT100*colorBDMode: on"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/xterm-256color.txt:112
msgid "! Love scrollback *VT100*saveLines: 5000 *VT100*scrollBar: true"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/xterm-256color.txt:115
msgid ""
"! Use -color app-defaults in /usr/X11R6/lib/X11/app-defaults *customization: "
"-color"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/xterm-256color.txt:118
msgid ""
"Make your new ~/.Xdefaults take effect without restarting X with: xrdb "
"-merge ~/.Xdefaults"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/xterm-256color.txt:122
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"7) Vim\n"
"To have syntax highlighting in vim, have this in your ~/.vimrc:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/xterm-256color.txt:124
msgid "syntax on"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/xterm-256color.txt:130
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"8) Log all the way out and come back in.  \n"
"You can do a combination of xrdb and sourcing your .bash_profile,\n"
"but your window manager will still think your TERM is xterm and\n"
"not xterm-color.  To eliminate confusion, just log out to xdm\n"
"or the login prompt and come back in.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/xterm-256color.txt:134
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"9) Checking colors\n"
"There are several nifty xterm tests in xc/programs/xterm/vttests.  \n"
"The fastest one for testing colors is 256colors2.pl.  Just run:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/xterm-256color.txt:137
msgid "chmod +x *.pl /256colors2.pl"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/xterm-256color.txt:140
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"10) Testing vim colors\n"
"Vim has a colortest program that you run with vim:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/xterm-256color.txt:142
msgid "vim /usr/share/vim/vim62/syntax/colortest.vim"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/xterm-256color.txt:145
msgid ">From inside vim, type: :source %"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/xterm-256color.txt:148
msgid ""
"I counted about 23 colors in this test, but it's nice seeing the words "
"associated with the colors."
msgstr ""

